==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sleeve
<hw>Sleeve</hw> <pr>(sl⟦emac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See
<er>Sleave</er>, untwisted thread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleeve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sleeve
<hw>Sleeve</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sleeve</ets>,
<ets>sleve</ets>, AS. <ets>sl<?/fe</ets>, <ets>sl<?/fe</ets>; akin to
<ets>sl<?/fan</ets> to put on, to clothe; cf. OD. <ets>sloove</ets> the
turning up of anything, <ets>sloven</ets> to turn up one's sleeves,
<ets>sleve</ets> a sleeve, G. <ets>schlaube</ets> a husk, pod.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The part of a garment which covers the arm; <as>as, the
<ex>sleeve</ex> of a coat or a gown</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A narrow channel of water.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Celtic Sea, called oftentimes the <qex>Sleeve</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A tubular part made
to cover, sustain, or steady another part, or to form a connection
between two parts.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A long bushing or thimble, as
in the nave of a wheel.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A short piece of pipe
used for covering a joint, or forming a joint between the ends of two
other pipes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A double tube of copper, in
section like the figure 8, into which the ends of bare wires are pushed
so that when the tube is twisted an electrical connection is made. The
joint thus made is called <col><b>a McIntire joint</b></col>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sleeve button</b></col>, <cd>a detachable button to
fasten the wristband or cuff.</cd> -- <col><b>Sleeve links</b></col>,
<cd>two bars or buttons linked together, and used to fasten a cuff or
wristband.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To laugh in the sleeve</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To laugh up one's sleeve</b></col></mcol> <cd>to
laugh privately or unperceived, especially while apparently preserving a
grave or serious demeanor toward the person or persons laughed at; that
is, perhaps, originally, by hiding the face in the wide sleeves of
former times.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To pinon the sleeve of</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>To hang on the sleeve of</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to
be, or make, dependent upon.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleeve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sleeve
<hw>Sleeve</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sleeved</conjf> <pr>(sl⟦emac⟧vd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sleeving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish with sleeves; to put
sleeves into; <as>as, to <ex>sleeve</ex> a coat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sleeved</ent>⟦br⟧
